Project 1: Covid Study

2023-03-10

Introduction

The purpose of this research project is to analyze statistical trends of the SARS-CoV-2 virus, or COVID-19, over time. Namely, we will examine the growth rate of cases, deaths, and various safety policies in different regions of the United States.

We’re using three datasets for our study which are to be joined by state. The first is a catalog of COVID-19 deaths over time, grouped by state. The data comes from the U.S. Department of Health & Human Services and was updated weekly until May 2021. Each row of the dataset represents a different state where the weekly death toll was recorded. The dataset can be found on The United States data catalog website. This data should assist in answering the question: what is the relationship between the timing of COVID-19 outbreak and the number of cases in different regions of the United States? This question seeks to examine whether there is a relationship between when COVID outbreaks occurred in different regions of the United States and the number of cases in those regions. Categorical variables in this dataset include geographic variables such as state names, region, division, and census region. Demographic variables, such as gender, age group, and race/ethnicity are also categorical. Numerical variables in the dataset include the number of confirmed cases and deaths per 100,000 population. Data variables are also numerical.

Our second dataset is a daily report of new COVID cases by state. The data is aggregated by USAFacts using data pulled from daily county government, health department, and hospital reports. State names, counties, metropolitan areas, and demographic variables compose the categorical variables of the dataset. Numerical variables include the number of confirmed COVID cases, confirmed deaths, and number of confirmed cases and deaths per 100,000. These variables are continuous. These data will help in answering the question: how were COVID-related deaths distributed across each state?

Our third dataset comes from the US State Policy Database. The database is run by researches from the Boston University School of Public Health; the school aggregates documentation from state governments and records the start and end dates of various policies designed to limit the spread of COVID-19. State names and post codes are stored as categorical variables, dates and logical variables are stored as dates and numerics respectively. We intend to investigate the relationship between various mandates and the spread of COVID-19; we expect more rigorous policy to correlate with a mitigated case count and death toll. In other words, how are COVID cases and deaths related to changing severity in COVID-related policy?

Dataset_1 <- read_csv("Dataset_1.csv")
## Rows: 60060 Columns: 15
## ── Column specification ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
## Delimiter: ","
## chr  (5): submission_date, state, created_at, consent_cases, consent_deaths
## dbl (10): tot_cases, conf_cases, prob_cases, new_case, pnew_case, tot_death,...
## 
## ℹ Use `spec()` to retrieve the full column specification for this data.
## ℹ Specify the column types or set `show_col_types = FALSE` to quiet this message.
Dataset_1 = Dataset_1 %>%
  group_by(state) %>% #group by state
  select(submission_date, state, new_case, new_death) %>% #only select these columns
  na.omit(new_case, new_death) %>% #omit the NA values
  arrange(state) %>% #alphabetical order
  separate(submission_date, into = c("%m", "%d", "%y")) %>% #separate by month, day, year.
  rename("year" = "%y") %>% #rename column
  select(year, state, new_case, new_death) %>% #only choose these variables
  group_by(year, state) %>% #group by these variables
  summarize(sum(new_case), sum(new_death)) #adding up all new cases and new deaths

Joining

After ensuring our datasets were tidied, we joined them into one central dataset. We first full joined our cases dataset and our mandates dataset; afterwards we right joined our deaths dataset to the already joined data. The documented code is as follows:

covidCases <- read_csv("covid2_tidy (1).csv")    # dataset 1
## Rows: 153 Columns: 3
## ── Column specification ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
## Delimiter: ","
## chr (1): State
## dbl (2): year, total_count
## 
## ℹ Use `spec()` to retrieve the full column specification for this data.
## ℹ Specify the column types or set `show_col_types = FALSE` to quiet this message.
maxCovid <- Dataset_1    # dataset 2

covidCases <- covidCases %>%
  rename(totCases = total_count) %>%    # rename for clarity
  mutate(year = as.numeric(year))
covidData <- covidCases %>%
  full_join(covidRules, by = c("State" = "stateAbbr")) %>%    # join on state
  rename(stateAbbr = State) %>%
  select(state, stateAbbr, year, everything())    # rearrange for legibility

covidData <- maxCovid %>%
  arrange(state) %>%
  rename(newCases = 'sum(new_case)', newDeaths = 'sum(new_death)') %>%
  mutate(year = as.numeric(year)) %>%    # change string year values to numerics
  right_join(covidData, by = c("state" = "stateAbbr", "year" = "year")) %>%
  select(state.y, state, year, everything()) %>%
  rename(stateAbbr = state, state = state.y) %>%
  select(-maskMandate2, -Emergency, -maskFine, -maskCite)    # remove extraneous columns

Unsurprisingly, we find that there are 51 states in our data set: the 50 states and District of Columbia.

At a glance, we can get a feel for if strict mask mandates were effective at limiting the spread of COVID. We’ll make a new variable called effective for states with strict mask mandate enforcement that evaluates to TRUE if the new cases in a given year were lower than the average new cases for that year.

covidData %>%
  filter(maskStrict == 1) %>%
  mutate(effective = ifelse(newCases < mean(newCases), TRUE, FALSE)) %>%
  summarize(mean(effective))
## # A tibble: 3 × 2
##    year `mean(effective)`
##   <dbl>             <dbl>
## 1  2020             0.6  
## 2  2021             0.6  
## 3  2022             0.571

We see here that 63% of states with strict punishments for disobeying mask mandates had a lower than average number of new cases for that year!

Additionally, we’ll add a categorical variable that represents the level of lockdown a state enforced. A state is considered to be under high lockdown if they issued a shelter-in-place order and were strict about enforcing mask mandates.

covidData <- covidData %>%
  mutate(lockdown_level = ifelse(stayHome==1 & maskMandate==1 & maskStrict==1, "High", "Low"))

Finally, we create a comprehensive summary variable.

covidData_summary <- covidData %>%
  group_by(state, year, lockdown_level) %>%
  summarize(total_cases = sum(totCases))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'state', 'year'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.

Discussion

Each figure shows how cases, new deaths, and lockdown precautions vary by state. We can use these insights to answer our research questions. Figures 1 and 2 chart the progression of COVID cases and deaths over time. In figure 1, we see that COVID cases increase dramatically for all states across all three years of our study. Interestingly, however, figure 2 shows a decrease in COVID deaths after 2021. This is likely due to vaccines, less deadlier strains, and other factors that effectively made COVID less lethal. Additionally, Figure 3 shows a correlation between number of COVID cases per state and severity of lockdown restrictions; states with higher lockdown levels faced fewer cases in 2021. This decrease in infection could be caused by the strict mandates, although it isn’t unlikely that people in states with more strict lockdowns are also warier of COVID’s spread. It’s difficult to separate correlation from causation with our limited data.

In hindsight, we had a difficult time tidying our data. It wasn’t easy to determine when our datasets were tidy, especially when working with such large amounts of information. It might be useful to trim unused data before tidying to make tidying data easier in the future. We also had a bit of a hard time making some of our visualizations. There are a lot of intricacies in ggplot2 where a small change can dramatically affect the final product. It was challenging to create attractive visuals, but we did grow more confident using ggplot’s more esoteric commands like facet_wrap() and theme().
